<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Pull-Up">Pull-Up</h3>



<p>The <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/pull-up" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">pull-up</a> is a powerful bodyweight exercise that intensely works the back muscles. During a traditional pull-up, the <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28846224/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">lats</a> can work at about <a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5548150/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">80% of their maximum capacity</a>. Thus, making it ideal for sculpting a more defined muscular back.</p>



<p>It also engages the <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30137823/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">biceps</a>, shoulders, and core, making it a staple in any <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/upper-body-bodyweight-workout" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">upper body bodyweight workout</a>. The exercise requires a pull-up bar or similar sturdy surface and can be modified for beginners or advanced athletes.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio vimeo-custom"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<iframe loading="lazy" title="Pull-Ups" src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/980208778?dnt=1&amp;app_id=122963" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen; picture-in-picture; clipboard-write"></iframe>
</div><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Pull-Up Guide. Video: Aliaksandr Makatserchyk</figcaption></figure>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">How To Do</h4>



<ol>
<li>Grip the pull-up bar with your hands slightly wider than shoulder-width, palms facing away from you.</li>



<li>Hang from the bar with your arms fully extended and shoulders engaged.</li>



<li>Pull your chest toward the bar by squeezing your shoulder blades together and driving your elbows down.</li>



<li>Lower yourself back to the starting position in an engaged motion.</li>
</ol>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Tips</h4>



<ul>
<li>Avoid using momentum or swinging; focus on controlled movements to maximize back engagement.</li>



<li>Keep your core tight to prevent arching or swaying during the exercise.</li>



<li>Initiate the pull with your back muscles, not your arms, to target the lats effectively.</li>



<li>Beginners can use resistance bands or an assisted pull-up machine to build strength.</li>



<li>Advanced athletes can add weight with a belt or hold the top position to increase intensity.</li>
</ul>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Optimal Sets And Reps</h4>



