<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Bodyweight-Single-Leg-Deadlift">Bodyweight Single-Leg Deadlift</h3>



<p>The <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/bodyweight-single-leg-deadlift" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">bodyweight single-leg deadlift</a> is a unilateral (one-sided) exercise that effectively works the <a href="https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/physiology/articles/10.3389/fphys.2021.694604/full" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">hamstrings</a> and <a href="https://europepmc.org/article/nbk/nbk538193" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">glutes</a>. It also engages your core and improves balance, coordination, and stability.&nbsp;</p>



<p>This movement is ideal for enhancing lower-body strength while addressing <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36035582/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">muscular imbalances</a>. This is because training one side at a time ensures that a stronger side doesn’t compensate for the weaker side.&nbsp;</p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio vimeo-custom"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<iframe loading="lazy" title="Bodyweight Single-leg Deadlifts" src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/980236694?dnt=1&amp;app_id=122963" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen; picture-in-picture; clipboard-write"></iframe>
</div><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Bodyweight Single-Leg Deadlift Guide. Video: Aliaksandr Makatserchyk</figcaption></figure>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">How To Do</h4>



<ol>
<li>Stand tall with your feet hip-width apart and engage your core for balance.</li>



<li>Shift your weight onto one leg, keeping a slight bend in the supporting knee.</li>



<li>Hinge forward at the hips while extending your other leg straight back.</li>



<li>Lower your torso until it’s parallel to the floor, forming a T shape with your body.&nbsp;</li>



<li>As you lower, reach the arm on the moving leg’s side towards the opposing foot.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Slowly return to the starting position by driving through your supporting heel and returning your arm to your side. Repeat on the other leg.</li>
</ol>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Tips</h4>



<ul>
<li>Keep your back flat and avoid rounding your shoulders to protect your spine.</li>



<li>Focus on keeping your hips and shoulders level to prevent rotation during the movement.</li>



<li>Engage your glutes to stabilize your pelvis and control the descent.</li>



<li>Beginners can use a wall or chair for support while improving balance.</li>
</ul>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Optimal Sets And Reps</h4>



